    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1894-11-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1894-11-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="65"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d65">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Gresham</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Dun</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 66.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1894-11-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 6, 1894</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The deplorable war between Japan and China endangers no policy of the United
                    States in Asia. Our attitude toward the belligerents is that of an impartial and
                    friendly neutral, desiring the welfare of both. If the struggle continues
                    without check to Japan’s military operations on land and sea, it is not
                    improbable that other powers having interests in that quarter may demand a
                    settlement not favorable to Japan’s future security and well-being. Cherishing
                    the most friendly sentiments of regard for Japan, the President directs that you
                    ascertain whether a tender of his good offices in the interests of a peace alike
                    honorable to both nations would be acceptable to the Government at Tokyo.</p>
            </div>
